ropic statements, though the timeframe is plausible given industry norms.\n\n**Sources:** No specific websites or links were provided in the research document.\n\n\n# RESEARCH\n## Report 1 Research\n### Research Summary: Claude Mythos Public Release Before September 2026\n\n#### Current Status of Claude Mythos\n\n**What we know:**\n- Claude Mythos (also referred to internally as \"Capybara\") is Anthropic's rumored next-generation model intended to succeed Claude Opus\n- As of my last training data (April 2024), Mythos has not been publicly released\n- Anthropic has not made official public announcements about Mythos specifications, timeline, or release date\n- References to Mythos primarily come from industry leaks, job postings, and unofficial sources rather than Anthropic statements\n\n#### Relevant Timeline Context\n\n**Anthropic's release cadence:**\n- Claude 3 family (Opus, Sonnet, Haiku) released March 2024\n- Typically 6-12 month gaps between major model releases\n- Anthropic has shown willingness to release models to public (via API and Claude.ai)\n\n**Forecasting period:** ~20 months from April 2024 to September 2026\n\n#### Key Considerations\n\n**Factors supporting a Yes resolution:**\n- 20-month window is substantial for a major AI company\n- Anthropic has demonstrated regular release cadence\n- Competitive pressure from other labs (OpenAI, Google, Meta) incentivizes releases\n- Public release doesn't require full deployment\u2014limited access qualifies\n\n**Factors supporting a No resolution:**\n- No official confirmation of Mythos existence or timeline from Anthropic\n- Safety testing and alignment work may extend timelines\n- Anthropic may choose different naming/branding\n- \"Equivalent\" model definition requires credible confirmation of tier equivalence\n\n#### Current Resolution Trajectory\n\nBased on available information, **the question remains highly uncertain** without official Anthropic statements. The timeframe is plausible given industry norms, but lack of public commitment creates significant ambiguity.\n\n# FORECASTS\n\n## R1: Forecaster 1 Reasoning\n### Analysis\n\n**(a) Time left until outcome is known:**\n96 days (from May 27, 2026 to September 1, 2026)\n\n**(b) Status quo outcome if nothing changed:**\nNO - Claude Mythos remains in limited preview access only, not released to the general public. Anthropic has explicitly stated they do not plan to make Claude Mythos Preview generally available.\n\n**(c) Scenario resulting in NO:**\nAnthropic maintains its current position of restricting Claude Mythos to the 11 organizations in the cybersecurity vulnerability-finding program. The company continues to prioritize safety testing and alignment work, deciding that a public release before September 2026 is premature. No equivalent model is released under alternative branding. This is the most consistent with Anthropic's stated intentions and cautious approach to deployment.\n\n**(d) Scenario resulting in YES:**\nAnthropic reverses its position and announces a public release of Claude Mythos (or an explicitly equivalent model) before September 1, 2026. This could occur due to competitive pressure, successful safety validation from the preview program, or strategic business decisions. The release could be limited (e.g., to verified users, specific countries, or Claude.ai subscribers) and still qualify as \"public.\"\n\n---\n\n### Rationale\n\nThe Wikipedia excerpt provided indicates that as of April 2026, Claude Mythos exists only in limited preview form with explicit statements that Anthropic \"does not plan to make Claude Mythos Preview generally available.\" This represents a clear, recent statement of intent against public release.\n\nWith only 96 days remaining and Anthropic having just made this restrictive announcement, the status quo strongly favors NO. Major AI companies rarely reverse such explicit policy statements within 3 months, especially regarding models with significant security implications.\n\nHowever, the resolution criteria are permissive\u2014any \"equivalent Claude model\" explicitly described as above Opus tier would qualify. This creates some tail-risk probability that Anthropic could release under different branding or that circumstances could change dramatically.\n\nThe base rate of status quo persistence in corporate AI policy, combined with Anthropic's explicit recent statement, heavily weights toward NO.\n\n**Probability: 18%**\n\n\n## R1: Forecaster 2 Reasoning\n### Analysis\n\n**(a) Time left until outcome is known:**\n96 days (from May 27, 2026 to September 1, 2026)\n\n**(b) Status quo outcome if nothing changed:**\nNO - Claude Mythos remains in limited preview access only, not released to the general public. Anthropic has explicitly stated they do not plan to make Claude Mythos Preview generally available.\n\n**(c) Scenario resulting in NO:**\nAnthropic maintains its current position: Claude Mythos remains restricted to the 11 organizations in the cybersecurity vulnerability-finding program. No public release occurs before September 1, 2026. Anthropic either continues the limited preview indefinitely or transitions to a different release strategy (e.g., waiting until 2027, or releasing under a different name/branding that doesn't meet the resolution criteria).\n\n**(d) Scenario resulting in YES:**\nAnthropic reverses course and announces a public release of Claude Mythos (or explicitly confirms an equivalent model under the \"Capybara\" or \"tier above Opus\" criteria) before September 1, 2026. This could occur via Claude.ai access, API availability, or other public channels. The company decides competitive or strategic pressures warrant broader availability despite earlier statements.\n\n---\n\n### Rationale\n\nThe Wikipedia excerpt provided indicates that as of late April 2026, Anthropic has **explicitly stated** it does not plan to make Claude Mythos Preview generally available. This is a strong, recent commitment against public release.\n\nWith only ~3 months remaining, reversing this stated position would require significant strategic recalculation. While possible, this goes against:\n- Anthropic's explicit recent statement\n- The company's demonstrated caution around powerful capabilities (cybersecurity vulnerabilities)\n- The status quo bias that organizations rarely reverse public commitments within 3 months\n\nThe limited preview access to 11 organizations does NOT meet the resolution criteria for \"public release,\" as the criteria require \"some members of the general public\" to access the model, not just pre-selected organizations.\n\nHowever, there is non-negligible probability that:\n- Anthropic changes strategic direction due to competitive pressure\n- An accidental public release occurs (similar to the Discord breach mentioned)\n- Anthropic redefines what constitutes \"public\" in a way that satisfies the criteria\n\nGiven the explicit recent statement against public release, the short timeframe remaining, and status quo bias, but acknowledging meaningful tail risk of reversal:\n\n**Probability: 18%**\n\n",
