anging threat landscapes.\n\n**What additional current information would be most valuable for your forecast?**\n\n# FORECASTS\n\n## R1: Forecaster 1 Reasoning\n### Analysis\n\n**(a) Time left until outcome is known:**\nApproximately 3 months and 5 days (from May 27, 2026 to September 1, 2026, UTC).\n\n**(b) Status quo outcome if nothing changed:**\nThe threat level remains at SEVERE. This is the baseline expectation, as threat levels typically exhibit considerable institutional inertia and the bar for downgrading from SEVERE is historically very high.\n\n**(c) A scenario resulting in NO outcome:**\nThe threat landscape remains characterized by persistent Islamist and extreme right-wing terrorist threats from individuals and small groups. Despite ongoing counterterrorism operations, no major breakthrough occurs that would justify downgrading. JTAC maintains SEVERE as appropriate given the continued assessment that an attack is \"highly likely.\" The threat level remains unchanged through August 31, 2026.\n\n**(d) A scenario resulting in YES outcome:**\nSignificant operational successes occur\u2014such as the disruption of multiple active plots, arrest of key threat actors, or substantial degradation of terrorist capability networks. Alternatively, the broader threat landscape shifts materially (e.g., de-escalation of international tensions, reduced radicalization indicators). JTAC conducts a reassessment and determines the threat has reduced to SUBSTANTIAL, with this reduction taking effect before September 1, 2026.\n\n---\n\n### Rationale\n\n**Status quo weighting:** Threat levels are deliberately conservative instruments. JTAC raised the level to SEVERE on April 30, 2026\u2014just 27 days ago\u2014citing long-term rising trends in both Islamist and extreme right-wing threats. This recent elevation suggests institutional assessment that conditions warrant the highest non-critical level.\n\n**Institutional inertia:** Downgrading from SEVERE within 3 months would requ