ut future market data.**\n\n# FORECASTS\n\n## R1: Forecaster 1 Reasoning\n### Forecasting Analysis: VIX Above 30 for 5+ Trading Days (April 20 - May 31, 2026)\n\n#### (a) Time Left Until Resolution\nToday is May 27, 2026. The question resolves on May 31, 2026 \u2014 **4 calendar days remain** (likely 3 trading days: May 28, 29, and possibly June 1 if we count into the next week, but the window closes May 31).\n\nThis is a **near-resolution question** where most of the outcome is already determined.\n\n#### (b) Status Quo Outcome If Nothing Changed\nAs of May 27, 2026, I need to assess: How many trading days between April 20 and May 27 has the VIX closed above 30?\n\nGiven the background context:\n- The VIX stood at 17.94 in mid-April 2026\n- It spiked to 35.75 during the U.S.\u2013Iran escalation in early April\n- The question window begins April 20 (after the acute phase of that crisis)\n\n**Reasonable inference:** The April escalation likely produced some VIX closes above 30 in late April, but by late May the market has likely stabilized. The VIX typically mean-reverts after geopolitical shocks unless conditions deteriorate further.\n\n**Status quo assumption:** The VIX has likely closed above 30 on **3-6 trading days** in the April 20 - May 27 window. This puts us near the threshold.\n\n#### (c) Scenario Resulting in NO\n- The VIX closed above 30 on **5 or fewer trading days** total in the April 20 - May 31 window\n- This occurs if: The Iran escalation shock dissipated by late April; markets repriced risk downward; the remaining 3 trading days in May close below 30\n- **Most likely outcome:** The acute crisis phase ended, volatility normalized, and we fall just short of the 6+ day threshold\n- Status quo bias suggests markets absorb shocks and revert to baseline; sustained stress regimes are rare\n\n#### (d) Scenario Resulting in YES\n- The VIX closed above 30 on **more than 5 trading days** (i.e., 6+) in the April 20 - May 31 window\n- This occurs if: The Iran crisis produced sustained elevated volatility through late April/early May; OR a new shock emerged in late May (market correction, economic data surprise, geopolitical escalation)\n- Requires either: (1) the initial shock was more persistent than typical, OR (2) a secondary shock occurred in late May\n- Less likely given that we're already at May 27 with limited time for new shocks to materialize\n\n#### Rationale\n\n**Key forecasting principles:**\n1. **Status quo bias:** Markets typically absorb shocks within 1-3 weeks. The Iran escalation occurred in early April; by late April/May, reversion to baseline is the default expectation.\n2. **Rarity of sustained stress:** VIX > 30 on 6+ days in a 6-week window requires either a major ongoing crisis or multiple shocks. Single-event spikes rarely sustain this long.\n3. **Time decay:** With only 3 trading days left (May 28-31), the outcome is largely locked in. Unless we're already at 5 days above 30, reaching 6+ is unlikely without a dramatic late-May shock.\n4. **Historical patterns:** Post-geopolitical-shock volatility typically peaks within days, then declines as risk premiums normalize.\n\n**Critical unknown:** The exact count of VIX closes > 30 between April 20 and May 27. \n\n**Best estimate:** Given the April escalation and typical volatility dynamics, the count is likely **4-5 days**, placing us just below or at the threshold. The remaining 3 trading days are unlikely to add enough to cross 6+ unless a new shock emerges (low probability at this late date).\n\n**Probability assessment:**\n- If current count is \u22644 days: ~15% chance of reaching 6+ (would need all remaining days above 30)\n- If current count is exactly 5 days: ~25% chance (need >1 of remaining 3 days above 30)\n- If current count is \u22656 days: ~95% chance (already resolved YES)\n\n**Weighted estimate:** Assuming the most likely scenario (4-5 days already occurred), the probability of YES is approximately **20-30%**.\n\n---\n\n**Probability: 25