ld\u2014unlikely given the stabilization narrative.\n\n#### (d) Scenario Resulting in Yes Outcome\nA renewed geopolitical or financial crisis erupts in late April or May 2026, causing sustained market stress. The VIX spikes above 30 and remains elevated for multiple consecutive days, accumulating 6+ total days above 30 for the full April 20 - May 31 window. This would require either: (1) a major new shock in late April that persisted into May, or (2) the Iran situation re-escalating significantly after an initial calm.\n\n---\n\n#### Rationale\n\n**Weighting the status quo heavily:** The background states that as of mid-April, the VIX had already spiked to 35.75 during the acute Iran escalation phase, but had retreated to 17.94 by mid-April. This suggests **market normalization was already underway** before the April 20 question window began. \n\nHistorical patterns show that:\n- VIX spikes above 30 are **clustered during acute crises**, not spread evenly\n- Once a shock is absorbed, the VIX typically returns to baseline within days to weeks\n- Sustained VIX > 30 for 5+ days requires either a prolonged crisis or repeated shocks\n\nGiven that we are now at May 27 with only 2 trading days remaining, and the acute Iran crisis was in early April (before the window), the probability that VIX has already accumulated 6+ days above 30 during April 20 - May 31 is **low**. The burden of proof is on a \"Yes\" outcome requiring either:\n1. Sustained stress from April 20 onward (unlikely given mid-April normalization), OR\n2. A new crisis in late May (only 2 days left to materialize)\n\n**Base rate consideration:** In typical years without major crises, VIX closes above 30 on <5% of trading days. The April 20 - May 31 window contains ~30 trading days. Reaching 6+ days (20% of trading days) requires abnormal conditions.\n\n---\n\n**Probability: 22%**\n\nThis reflects:\n- Low likelihood that the VIX sustained above 30 for 5+ days during the already-elapsed April 20 - May 27 period